<h1 class = "page-header">CLI</h1>
<p>Back in the day, computers didnt have Graphical User Interfaces (GUIs). It used to be that you would flip a switch on the back of the computer, and, after a few minutes of beeping and whirring, you would be presented with a command prompt. This is also where we are going to begin. Lets go ahead and open up iTerm2.
</p>

<h4 class = "page-header">Basic Structure</h4>
<p>If you take a look you will see that your computer name shows followed by a ~ which represents you are in the home directory. The $ represents the command prompt</p>

<h4 class = "page-header">Say Something</h4>
<p>
  Now lets say something:
  <pre>echo "hello world"</pre>
</p>

<h4 class = "page-header">Whats My Username?</h4>
<p>
  Now lets figure out our username:
  <pre>whoami</pre>
</p>

<h4 class = "page-header">Paths</h4>
<p>
  Everything in the filesystem is nested underneath the root folder, "/". The Absolute Path of an item in the filesystem is its location relative to the root folder. To get to the root you can type:
  <pre>cd ~</pre>
</p>

<p>The Relative Path of file or folder is its location from the current working directory. The absolute path is from the root folder</p>

<p>
  To get our absolute path of our working directory:
  <pre>pwd</pre>
</p>

<h4 class = "page-header">Viewing Files</h4>
<p>
  When working on the CLI we work primarily with files and directories. Lets view a file
  <pre>ls</pre>
</p>

